<section class="row"><div class="six columns"><h2>Showcasing product features</h2></div></section>

<section class="row"><div class="one-half column"><p>We wanted to showcase features of the mobile product in an interactive way, similar to a demo “try before you buy”, on the page. However, building out that kind of interactivity can be really resource intensive. We decided to try making “videos” of the product features instead. I came up with some testing</p></div>
<div class="one-half column"><p>
ideas using Airbnb’s app as an example, since we’d gotten
good customer feedback about trusting Airbnb as an example. Although the page was originally designed for our iOS beta launch, I wanted to keep the phones neutral so we could reuse the graphics for our Android launch as well. </p></div></section>

<section class="row"><div class="one-half column"><p>1. Making visual changes with the WYSIWYG Editor</p><p>
Say you want to test connected sign-ins and predict that more users will login through Facebook than Google. You can drag and drop the FB login button to the top of the screen. </p></div>

<div class="one-half column"><img src="/uploads/mobile-lp/mobilelp01.gif"></div>
</section>

<section class="row"><div class="one-half column"><p>2. Making code level changes with developer tools</p><p>
Say you want to be able to test app engagement with and without a login screen. Using developer tools, you can custom create an on/off switch for a login screen.</p></div>

<div class="one-half column"><img src="/uploads/mobile-lp/mobilelp02.gif"></div>
</section>

<section class="row"><div class="one-half column"><p>3. Instantly roll out changes. </p><p>
Now that you have a couple of variations to test, you can deploy the changes without having to go through an appstore review. In this example we show the two test variations we made through the WYSIWYG editor and Developer Tools.</p></div>

