<h2>Hacking the header image</h2>
<section class="row"><div class="one-half column">We needed a specific header image that was difficult to find so we made our own using free stock photos and a customized app screen. Though it was a bit hacky, this allowed us to have complete control over the header image as well as provide a reusable process for future product marketing pages.</div></section>


<img src="/uploads/mobile-lp/mobilelp-photo01.jpg">
<section class="row"><div class="one-half column"><p>First step was finding an nicely photoshopped hand holding a phone, then add your own screen. Second step was finding a stock photo to put it on.</p></div>
<div class="one-half column"><p>Create the illusion of depth of field by blurring the stock photo behind the photoshopped hand holding a phone.
</p></div>
</section>


<img src="/uploads/mobile-lp/mobilelp-photo02.jpg">
<section class="row"><div class="one-half column"><p>Blur the entire image, just as you might with any stock photo you want to put text over. </p></div>
<div class="one-half column"><p>Overlay a brand color on the image to make the treatment specific to your company’s.
</p></div>
</section>


<section class="row"><div class="one-half column"><h2>Animated gif timing logic</h2></div><div class="one-half column"><p>Animations and videos can really affect page performance. When building out the page, we decided on gifs (<a href="http://invisionapp.com" target="_new">similar to InVision</a>) due to file sizes and talked through the timing of when the gifs play as you’re scrolling down the page as well as how that’d translate on mobile since there aren’t hover states. <a href="http://optimizely.com/mobile" target="_new">Check out the page</a> and see how we did it. Mockup of the final site below.</p></div>
</section>

